       How to Parse CLI Arguments Using the Args Package

       Main Classes

       The args package provides three core classes for CLI argument parsing:

       1. ArgParser - Defines and parses command-line arguments
       2. ArgResults - Contains the parsed arguments and provides access to values
       3. Option - Represents individual options and flags (defined internally)

       Creating an ArgParser

       var parser = ArgParser();

       Optional parameters:
       - allowTrailingOptions (default: true) - Allow options after positional arguments
       - usageLineLength (default: null) - Maximum line length for help text wrapping

       Defining Flags

       Flags are boolean values that are either set or unset:

       parser.addFlag('verbose', abbr: 'v', defaultsTo: false, help: 'Verbose output');
       parser.addFlag('name', negatable: false);  // Disable --no-name negation

       Key parameters:
       - abbr - Single character shorthand (e.g., -v)
       - defaultsTo - Default boolean value (must be bool)
       - negatable - Allow --no- prefix to negate (default: true)
       - help - Description for usage text
       - callback - Function invoked with the flag's value
       - hide - Hide from usage text (default: false)
       - aliases - Alternative names for the flag

       Defining Options

       Options take string values:

       parser.addOption('mode',
           abbr: 'm',
           defaultsTo: 'debug',
           help: 'Mode in which to run',
           allowed: ['debug', 'release']);

       parser.addOption('out',
           help: 'The output path',
           valueHelp: 'path');

       Key parameters:
       - abbr - Single character shorthand
       - defaultsTo - Default string value
       - allowed - List of valid values (validates at parse time)
       - allowedHelp - Map describing allowed values
       - valueHelp - Placeholder name for the value in usage text
       - mandatory - Option must be provided (default: false)
       - callback - Function invoked with the option's value
       - help - Description for usage text
       - hide - Hide from usage text

       Defining Multi-Options

       Options that accept multiple values:

       parser.addMultiOption('mode');

       Supports both --mode on --mode off and --mode on,off syntax (comma splitting
       enabled by default).

       Key parameters:
       - splitCommas - Allow comma-separated values (default: true)
       - Other parameters similar to addOption

       Parsing Arguments

       var results = parser.parse(['--mode', 'debug', '--verbose', 'file.txt']);

       Returns an ArgResults object.

       Accessing Parsed Values

       From the ArgResults object:

       // For flags (returns bool)
       bool verbose = results.flag('verbose');

       // For options (returns String or null)
       String? mode = results.option('mode');

       // For multi-options (returns List<String>)
       List<String> modes = results.multiOption('mode');

       // Check if explicitly provided (vs. using default)
       bool wasParsed = results.wasParsed('mode');

       // Non-option positional arguments
       List<String> remaining = results.rest;

       // Access by name using bracket notation
       dynamic value = results['mode'];

       // Get all available option names
       Iterable<String> optionNames = results.options;

       Displaying Help

       print(parser.usage);  // Generates formatted help text

       Command-Line Syntax Examples

       With parser.addOption('name', abbr: 'n'):
       - --name=value
       - --name value
       - -nvalue
       - -n value

       With parser.addFlag('verbose', abbr: 'v'):
       - --verbose or -v (set to true)
       - --no-verbose (set to false, if negatable)
       - -vfi (collapse multiple flag abbreviations)

       Full Example

       void main(List<String> args) {
         var parser = ArgParser();

         parser.addOption('compiler',
             abbr: 'c',
             defaultsTo: 'none',
             allowed: ['none', 'dart2js']);

         parser.addFlag('verbose',
             abbr: 'v',
             defaultsTo: false,
             help: 'Verbose output');

         var results = parser.parse(args);

         print('Compiler: ${results.option('compiler')}');
         print('Verbose: ${results.flag('verbose')}');
         print('Remaining: ${results.rest}');
       }

